Task Description¶

Imagine that you’re working for an airline. Your task is to reduce their support team workload by creating a chatbot that can direct visitors to the correct page (e.g. the flight search). Unknown inputs are still handled with the help of a human.

The product team is asking you to help them build that tool and to estimate the workload reduction. Further, a process should be mapped out to ensure the bot’s accuracy over time. What would your advice be?

Note: Please use any of the free popular Notebook providers (Kaggle, Colab, ...) or upload the final notebook to GitHub and share it with us. Python is strongly preferred (unless there’s a good reason to use something else).

Problem statement¶

As a data scientist/machine learning engineer working for an airline, we want to reduce the workload of support team so that we can save time and manpower.

Current State¶

Right now, it is a manual process to direct people to the correct page when they have support queries.

Stakeholder Proposed Solution¶

Would it be possible to automate this process by building a machine learning model that can help to automatically direct most visitors to the right page?

Key Assumptions for Stakeholder Proposed Solution¶

  1. That we have or can obtain enough labelled data to support the model identifying intents (assumed true, atis dataset)
  2. That a machine learning model can automatically predict what page people want to go to (intent) from the their queries (to be validated)
  3. That we do have concrete webpages that maps to each of the identified intents (assumed true) - this could be in a lookup table, so perhaps if the result is atis_flights, we return www.atis.com/flights
  4. That we would not have the chatbot ask queries for more details where there is some uncertainty (assumed true, as unknown inputs handled with help of human)

Alternatives to stakeholder proposed solution that also solve the problem of reduce the workload of support team¶

  1. Improving UI/UX of support pages (i.e. most people looked for X and Y data, is this what you are looking for?)
We should always think about alternatives because sometimes, it is possible for alternative solutions to achieve the initial business objective without machine learning, in some cases at a much lower cost and effort. In this case, we assume that the machine learning approach was chosen by the stakeholder¶

Additional Stakeholder Requirements¶

  1. To estimate the workload reduction - specifically measure how often human intervention is required?
  2. Further, a process should be mapped out to ensure the bot’s accuracy over time.

Approach¶

Step 1. Validate assumption 1 - that it is possible to accurately identify intents. We validate this by building models to do intent prediction, analysing the accuracy, which gets us our first PoC, and also helps us estimate workload reduction

Step 2. Design a framework around PoC to measure performance over time

Step 1 : Validating Assumptions and Building PoC Model¶

Overall approach

  1. Some EDA, cleaning up
  2. classical model, using BoW, tfidf and Random Forests (~93% F1 score)
  3. neural pre-trained BERT model to finetune on problem, and see if we can improve results (~98% F1 score)

Step 2 : Architecting¶

  1. How does model fit into entire framework?
  2. Track and visualise metrics and predictions
  3. How to ensure the bot’s accuracy over time.

Step 1 : Validating Assumptions and Building PoC Model¶

from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfTransformer, CountVectorizer
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.multioutput  import MultiOutputClassifier

text_clf = Pipeline([
     ('vect', CountVectorizer(stop_words="english")),
     ('tfidf', TfidfTransformer()),
     ('clf', MultiOutputClassifier(RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=40), n_jobs=-1)),
 ])

import matplotlib
matplotlib.use('nbAgg')

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

rf_model = text_clf.named_steps["clf"].estimators_[8]

get_importances = []
for feature, importance in zip(text_clf.named_steps["vect"].get_feature_names(), rf_model.feature_importances_):
    get_importances.append((feature, importance))
get_importances.sort(key=lambda x: x[1],reverse=True)
# find out what the model uses to predict
plt.figure(figsize = (6,5))
plt.barh([i[0] for i in reversed(get_importances[:30])],width=[i[1] for i in reversed(get_importances[:30])])
print(get_importances[:30])
plt.xticks(size=10,rotation=90)
plt.show()

Model training code :¶

from transformers import AutoModelForSequenceClassification, TrainingArguments, Trainer
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_fscore_support, accuracy_score
batch_size=4

tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_name, use_fast=True)

def preprocess_function(examples):
    return tokenizer(examples["text"], truncation=True,max_length=512)


def tokenize(batch):
    batch['labels'] = [torch.tensor(list(float(j) for j in i),dtype=torch.float64) for i in batch['labels']]
    return batch

dataset = dataset.map(tokenize, batched=True)
encoded_dataset = dataset.map(preprocess_function, batched=True)
encoded_dataset = encoded_dataset.remove_columns("text")

encoded_dataset.set_format("torch")
encoded_dataset = (encoded_dataset
          .map(lambda x : {"float_labels": x["labels"].to(torch.float)}, remove_columns=["labels"])
          .rename_column("float_labels", "labels"))

model = model.to("cuda")

metric_name = "f1"

args = TrainingArguments(
    "airline_intents_model",
    evaluation_strategy = "epoch",
    save_strategy = "epoch",
    learning_rate=2e-5,
    per_device_train_batch_size=batch_size,
    per_device_eval_batch_size=batch_size,
    num_train_epochs=10,
    weight_decay=0.01, 
    load_best_model_at_end=True,
    metric_for_best_model=metric_name,
    report_to="wandb"
)


def compute_metrics(pred):
    labels = pred.label_ids
    preds = []
    for prediction in pred.predictions:
        preds.append([1 if i>=1 else 0 for i in prediction])
    precision, recall, f1, _ = precision_recall_fscore_support(labels, preds, average='micro')
    acc = accuracy_score(labels, preds)
    return {
        'accuracy': acc,
        'f1': f1,
        'precision': precision,
        'recall': recall
    }

trainer = Trainer(
model,
args,
train_dataset=encoded_dataset["train"],
eval_dataset=encoded_dataset["eval"],
tokenizer=tokenizer,
compute_metrics=compute_metrics
)

trainer.train()

model.save_pretrained(f"../models/model_airline_intents.pkl")

Step 2 : Architecting¶
    

  • How do we deploy a system that can maintain accuracy over time, is scalable, has visible metrics and logs, and can also be extended further? 
    • 

  • See below for final design and architecture for monitoring and visibility of deployed intents model
    • 

  • Big idea is we want to save prediction results as well as whatever feedback metrics we can get from user in a database so that we can subsequently use the data to improve the model, as well as visualise those metrics to be sure that our model is still accurate and doing well
    • 



Component choices¶
    

  • Backend - fastAPI - generally the fastest API backend in python, uses ASGI and also comes with free swagger API documentation
    • 

  • Metrics storage - prometheus - great time series database for storing real-time metrics
    • 

  • Metrics visualisation - grafana - great visualisation tool for metrics
    • 

  • Model Registry - MLFlow - good model registry framework, used to track and register models that would be deployed
    •
